04601nam a22005775i 9780228013686DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280136867 a10.1515/97802280136862doi  a(DE-B1597)656161  a(OCoLC)1394872626  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aF1031.5.G68bA35 2023 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a971.05/10922231 aAkenson, Don, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Orangeman, Second Edition :bThe Life and Times of Ogle Gowan, Second Edition /cDon Akenson.  aSecond edition 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface -- tOld World Inheritance -- tRumours of War, 1798 -- tThe Great Rising, 1798 -- tLearning the Language of Life, 1803–23 -- tFolds in Fortune, 1823–24 -- tTrials of a Young Married Man, 1824–26 -- tFamily Pride, 1826–29 -- tMining a New Land -- tA Very Fast Start, 1829–30 -- tBecoming an Immigrant Leader, 1831–33 -- tA Real Winner, 1833–35 -- tLocal Hero, 1835–36 -- tLoyalism Incarnate, 1836–38 -- tJust Rewards -- tThe Brass Ring, 1838–41 -- tA Certain Bluff Humanity, 1841–44 -- tA Fine Chance, 1844–48 -- tThe Black Flag, 1848–52 -- tBig City, 1852–56 -- tRecessional, 1856–76 -- tThe Gowan Legacy -- tA Note on Sources0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom the end of the Napoleonic Wars to Confederation, central Canada was awash with migrants from the British Isles and their cultural values. The raw prejudice that they brought with them – against the French, the Catholics, and even Yanks and Europeans – bound together the eventual political majority in Ontario. The Orangeman uses the life of Ogle Gowan, an Irish Protestant upstart from County Wexford who turned central Canada Orange, to explore these forces.Gowan was ambitious, malicious, and mendacious, but by the time of Confederation the Orange Order was the largest alliance of men in the country – the foundation of the coalition of conservative Protestants that sculpted Canadian politics in the century that followed. Don Akenson uses his skills as a historian and a novelist in respecting the historical record. The Orangeman is a lively and entertaining fictional biography, and in Akenson’s telling Gowan crosses swords with William Lyon Mackenzie and goes pub-crawling with the young John A. Macdonald.One never knows everything about a historical person or event; sometimes the right thing to do is to speculate sensibly and, if possible, have a little fun along the way. Akenson shows us Canadian loyalism, constitutionalism, and deference to state authority on one side of the coin, and on the flip side, the successful attempt by one group of Canadians to do down the other. This is real history, real life: as yesterday, so today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCanada-History-19th century. 0aGowan, Ogle Robert,-1803-1876. 0aIrishzCanadaxHistoryy19th century. 0aOrangemenzCanadavBiography. 0aOrangemen-Canada. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311127195808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP w/o University of Toronto Press 2023 eBook Packagez978311143542840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978022801368640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228013686423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228013686/original  a978-3-11-127195-8  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-3-11-143542-8  ACUP w/o University of Toronto Press 2023 eBook Packageb2023  aGBV-deGruyter-a